ALGORITHM:
Step 1: START
Step 2: Set counter = 1
Step 3: While counter <= 200, do Steps 4-8
Step 4: INPUT student_name, matric_no, ca_score, exam_score
Step 5: COMPUTE total_score = ca_score + exam_score
Step 6: DISPLAY student_name, matric_no, ca_score, exam_score, total_score
Step 7: INCREMENT counter by 1
Step 8: END WHILE
Step 9: STOP

FLOWCHART DESCRIPTION:
The flowchart begins with a Start oval, followed by initializing counter = 1. A diamond decision box checks if counter <= 200. If YES, parallelogram boxes handle INPUT of name, matric, CA, exam. A rectangle processes total = CA + exam. A parallelogram displays all info. Counter increments by 1. Flow returns to the decision. If NO, flow goes to STOP.

PROGRAM (in C):
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    char name[50];
    char matric[20];
    float ca_score, exam_score, total_score;
    int counter;

    for (counter = 1; counter <= 200; counter++) {
        printf("\nStudent %d:\n", counter);
        printf("Enter name: ");
        scanf("%s", name);
        printf("Enter matric number: ");
        scanf("%s", matric);
        printf("Enter CA score: ");
        scanf("%f", &ca_score);
        printf("Enter exam score: ");
        scanf("%f", &exam_score);

        total_score = ca_score + exam_score;

        printf("\nName: %s\n", name);
        printf("Matric: %s\n", matric);
        printf("CA: %.1f\n", ca_score);
        printf("Exam: %.1f\n", exam_score);
        printf("Total: %.1f\n", total_score);
    }

    return 0;
}

A for loop (definite iteration or counter-controlled loop) is the most appropriate for the solution in question 1b.

The for loop is preferred because:

1. The number of iterations is known in advance — exactly 200 students must be processed. The for loop is specifically designed for situations where the number of repetitions is predetermined.

2. The for loop combines initialization (counter = 1), condition (counter <= 200), and increment (counter++) in a single line, making the code compact, readable, and less error-prone.

3. The counter variable cleanly tracks progress through the 200 students.

The syntax is:
for (initialization; condition; increment) {
    // body
}

For our problem:
for (counter = 1; counter <= 200; counter++) {
    // Accept input, compute score, display output
}

A while loop could work but would require the counter to be initialized before the loop and incremented inside the body, increasing the risk of forgetting the increment (infinite loop). A do-while loop is unsuitable because it guarantees at least one execution before testing the condition, which is unnecessary here since we want to process exactly 200 iterations starting from 1.

ALGORITHM:
Step 1: START
Step 2: Set counter = 1
Step 3: While counter <= 80, do Steps 4-10
Step 4: INPUT staff_name, staff_id, hours_worked
Step 5: IF hours_worked <= 40 THEN
Step 6:   gross_pay = hours_worked * 10.00
Step 7: ELSE
Step 8:   gross_pay = (40 * 10.00) + ((hours_worked - 40) * 50.00)
Step 9: END IF
Step 10: DISPLAY staff_name, staff_id, hours_worked, gross_pay
Step 11: INCREMENT counter by 1
Step 12: END WHILE
Step 13: STOP

PROGRAM (in C):
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    char name[50], staff_id[20];
    float hours, gross_pay;
    int i;

    for (i = 1; i <= 80; i++) {
        printf("\nStaff %d:\n", i);
        printf("Enter name: ");
        scanf("%s", name);
        printf("Enter staff ID: ");
        scanf("%s", staff_id);
        printf("Enter hours worked: ");
        scanf("%f", &hours);

        if (hours <= 40) {
            gross_pay = hours * 10.00;
        } else {
            gross_pay = (40 * 10.00) + ((hours - 40) * 50.00);
        }

        printf("\nName: %s\n", name);
        printf("Staff ID: %s\n", staff_id);
        printf("Hours: %.1f\n", hours);
        printf("Gross Pay: N%.2f\n", gross_pay);
    }
    return 0;
}

FLOWCHART DESCRIPTION:
Start → Initialize counter = 1 → Decision: counter <= 80? If NO → Stop. If YES → Input name, ID, hours → Decision: hours <= 40? If YES → gross = hours * 10. If NO → gross = 400 + (hours-40)*50 → Display all info → counter++ → Loop back to counter <= 80 check.

A loop is a control structure in programming that allows a block of code to be repeated multiple times. Loops are essential for processing collections of data, performing repetitive calculations, and implementing algorithms that require iteration.

THREE LOOPING STRUCTURES:

1. FOR LOOP:
for (initialization; condition; increment) {
    // body
}
Example: for (i = 1; i <= 10; i++) { printf("%d", i); }
The for loop is used when the number of iterations is known in advance. It combines all three components in one line.

2. WHILE LOOP:
initialization;
while (condition) {
    // body
    increment;
}
Example: i = 1; while (i <= 10) { printf("%d", i); i++; }
The while loop is a pre-test loop — it checks the condition before executing the body. The body may not execute at all if the condition is initially false.

3. DO-WHILE LOOP:
initialization;
do {
    // body
    increment;
} while (condition);
Example: i = 1; do { printf("%d", i); i++; } while (i <= 10);
The do-while loop is a post-test loop — it executes the body first, then checks the condition. The body always executes at least once.

THREE COMPONENTS OF A LOOP:

1. INITIALIZATION: Setting the loop counter variable to its starting value before the loop begins. Example: i = 1. This happens once, before the first iteration.

2. CONDITION: A Boolean expression that is evaluated before each iteration. The loop continues to execute as long as the condition is true. When it becomes false, the loop terminates. Example: i <= 10.

3. INCREMENT (Update): Modifying the loop counter variable after each iteration to move toward the termination condition. Example: i++ (increases i by 1). Without this, the loop becomes infinite.

Selection (also called decision-making or branching) is a control structure that allows a program to choose between two or more alternative paths of execution based on whether a condition evaluates to true or false. It enables programs to make decisions and respond differently to different situations.

TYPE 1: IF-ELSE STATEMENT
The if-else statement tests a Boolean condition and executes one of two code blocks:

    if (condition) {
        // executed if condition is true
    } else {
        // executed if condition is false
    }

FLOWCHART for if-else:
    [Start] → <Condition?> —Yes→ [Block A] ——→ [Join] → [Next]
                     |
                    No
                     |
                   [Block B] ——→ [Join]

Example: if (marks >= 50) printf("Pass"); else printf("Fail");

The if-else-if ladder extends this to test multiple conditions:
    if (condition1) { block A }
    else if (condition2) { block B }
    else { block C }

TYPE 2: SWITCH-CASE STATEMENT
The switch statement selects among multiple alternatives based on the value of an integer or character expression:

    switch (expression) {
        case value1: // block A; break;
        case value2: // block B; break;
        default:     // block C; break;
    }

FLOWCHART for switch:
    [Start] → [Evaluate expression] → <Match value1?> —Yes→ [Block A] → [Break] → [Next]
                                             |
                                            No
                                             |
                                    <Match value2?> —Yes→ [Block B] → [Break]
                                             |
                                            No
                                             |
                                           [Default Block C]

Example: switch(day) { case 1: printf("Monday"); break; case 2: printf("Tuesday"); break; default: printf("Other"); }

The switch is more efficient than multiple if-else when comparing one variable against many discrete values. The break statement prevents fall-through to subsequent cases.
